And then we'll talk about eating meditation, which those of you who've been here, you know, will know that it's one of my obsessive teachings.

15
00:02:15,306 --> 00:02:19,713
So suppose a couple, so we're back in the desert.

16
00:02:19,753 --> 00:02:26,104
Suppose a couple, husband and wife, had taken limited provisions and were traveling through a desert.

17
00:02:27,004 --> 00:02:29,849
They have with them their only son, dear and beloved,

18
00:02:30,758 --> 00:02:57,542
then in the middle of the desert their limited provisions would be used up and exhausted while the rest of the desert remains to be crossed the husband and wife would think our limited provisions have been used up and are exhausted while the rest of the desert remains to be crossed let us kill our only son dear and beloved and prepare dried and spiced meat

19
00:02:58,417 --> 00:03:01,901
By eating our son's flesh, we can cross the rest of the desert.

20
00:03:03,042 --> 00:03:05,183
Let not all three of us perish.

21
00:03:07,646 --> 00:03:09,068
And they do that, of course.

22
00:03:09,108 --> 00:03:11,850
They kill and they prepare dried and roasted meat.

23
00:03:13,051 --> 00:03:25,925
So cannibalism doesn't particularly appeal to us, but this is a very, very strong image for telling us that hunger is one of our basic fears.

24
00:03:27,627 --> 00:03:33,579
And that when we eat, we ought to eat with right intention, not for indulgence sake, but we'll come to that.

25
00:03:35,342 --> 00:03:41,875
None of us really, I mean, maybe you have, but none of us really have experienced hunger.

26
00:03:42,676 --> 00:03:44,319
We've experienced being peckish.

27
00:03:44,670 --> 00:03:47,394
And then just going for that evening piece of toast.

28
00:03:48,294 --> 00:03:55,201
And we might have ended up a day in some peculiar situation where we haven't eaten.

29
00:03:55,842 --> 00:03:57,465
And when we get home, we're famished.

30
00:03:57,925 --> 00:04:01,489
But actually, we've never really experienced hunger.

31
00:04:02,330 --> 00:04:03,532
That annoying feeling.

32
00:04:04,573 --> 00:04:05,854
I certainly haven't.

33
00:04:06,354 --> 00:04:11,319
Where you really do believe that if you don't get some food, you're dying.

34
00:04:12,193 --> 00:04:41,711
and uh you can see some of the gaunt faces in the um in the refugees um and for me going back to the 60s and 70s where there were famines in india especially uh i've mentioned already the um uh the uh the myth the greek myth of um uh eriskathon who um upset the goddess demeter uh the the um the um

35
00:04:42,569 --> 00:04:45,432
Roman name was Ceres, from which we get cereal.

36
00:04:45,771 --> 00:04:52,478
She was in charge of all that grows, all the stuff that people eat.

37
00:04:53,259 --> 00:04:56,242
And he went and built a banqueting hall over her shrine.

38
00:04:56,422 --> 00:05:06,192
So she cursed him with this insatiable hunger, and he ends up eating all the food, everybody, his own family, and finally himself.

39
00:05:07,954 --> 00:05:10,415
So this is a myth about

40
00:05:10,867 --> 00:05:17,255
what happens when you're actually really hungry, right?

41
00:05:17,456 --> 00:05:22,963
She cursed him with this insatiable hunger.

42
00:05:23,824 --> 00:05:32,375
Now, I did meet a man in Sri Lanka many years ago who told me that he had actually got lost out in the wilderness in the US.

43
00:05:33,278 --> 00:05:36,442
And he'd got to this stage of real hunger.

44
00:05:36,901 --> 00:05:40,487
And he said, you know, come a point where he caught a bird

45
00:05:41,007 --> 00:05:49,035
a large bird, let's say a pigeon or something, and he actually ripped it apart and ate the raw flesh.

46
00:05:49,456 --> 00:06:03,951
So that gives you an idea of how hunger, when it gets right to the point of life or death, becomes utterly overwhelming, really.

47
00:06:04,711 --> 00:06:06,052
The same with thirst, of course.

48
00:06:07,567 --> 00:06:31,389
So I just wanted to take this opportunity, really, to reintroduce some of you, because you might not have worked with me, but remind the rest of you about eating meditation and how we can use it, especially if we're off these two or three days and there's a tendency to, well, have a good meal.

49
00:06:32,569 --> 00:06:36,934
And there are three things when we're eating that we have to try and distinguish.

50
00:06:37,487 --> 00:06:40,610
in order to liberate ourselves from indulgence.

51
00:06:41,351 --> 00:06:48,057
Now, we won't liberate ourselves from indulgence unless we see the consequences.

52
00:06:48,798 --> 00:06:54,564
And the problem is that while we're indulging ourselves, it's great, I mean, it's nibbana, what's the problem?

53
00:06:55,884 --> 00:07:02,151
But it's only afterwards that we begin to realise that there is quite a lot of suffering involved.

54
00:07:02,170 --> 00:07:06,735
And the first one, of course, is just that obsessive nature

55
00:07:07,002 --> 00:07:33,802
indulgence you know having to have we're not I mean just the morning cup of tea try and give that up for a while or coffee and you'll see how obsessive it is and if you look at any of your habits and you you try and stop them you'll see that there's a real strong desire coming up from that habit which demands to be satisfied to be gratified really is the right words of a gratification

56
00:07:35,807 --> 00:07:42,096
And the second problem would be frustration.

57
00:07:42,536 --> 00:07:45,158
Frustration always comes when you can't get what you want.

58
00:07:45,680 --> 00:07:50,865
So, you know, just look at the past week you've been in and see how many times you've been frustrated.

59
00:07:51,266 --> 00:07:57,053
Somebody's not behaved the way you wanted them to, a family member, somebody at work, whatever.

60
00:07:59,237 --> 00:08:01,540
Some piece of equipment hasn't worked for you.

61
00:08:01,560 --> 00:08:02,680
You're frustrated.

62
00:08:02,701 --> 00:08:04,362
The shopping didn't work.

63
00:08:04,629 --> 00:08:06,072
arrive at the right time.

64
00:08:06,552 --> 00:08:07,553
The bus was late.

65
00:08:07,574 --> 00:08:08,596
It goes on and on and on.

66
00:08:09,156 --> 00:08:10,398
And what you feel is anger.

67
00:08:10,699 --> 00:08:13,161
It's a frustration at not getting what you want.

68
00:08:14,704 --> 00:08:21,454
And, of course, once we drop all that, we just begin to establish an equanimity with the way things are.

69
00:08:21,754 --> 00:08:23,016
This is the way it is.

70
00:08:23,076 --> 00:08:28,002
That's the constant phrase we have to repeat to ourselves.

71
00:08:28,303 --> 00:08:29,365
This is the way it is.

72
00:08:29,444 --> 00:08:32,089
What's the point of getting upset?

73
00:08:32,575 --> 00:09:00,995
grief uh grief at loss you know you've only got to think if somebody actually you know went off with your um mobile phone that's a heavy grief that is definitely our lives are now wrapped up into in that little machine uh but of course grief takes on a much deeper meaning as we mentioned in the other day when we lose somebody who we're attached to so grief is always waiting for us when we are possessing something or

74
00:09:01,279 --> 00:09:31,134
worse identifying with us and identifying with ourselves and then underneath all that there is this anxiety there's an anxiety of loss uh you know that's why we have insurance uh some of it's realistic of course you want to insure your uh house my i had a cousin who uh who thought the insuring your house was just a you know it was a it was a what do you call it just a trick just to get money out of you so he never paid insurance for his house

75
00:09:31,503 --> 00:09:38,254
And then there was one very, very bad storm where his roof caved in.

76
00:09:38,274 --> 00:09:52,616
Now, I don't know whether he made up his money, how much that roof cost him and whether actually over a long period of time, 30 odd years or so, 30 odd years, he never paid any insurance.

77
00:09:52,758 --> 00:09:56,504
He would have actually saved some money if he had paid the insurance.

78
00:09:58,066 --> 00:09:58,606
But

79
00:09:58,807 --> 00:10:11,465
You know, when we buy anything from something like, you know, like a laptop or something, they always want to give you insurance, you know, to make it last three years so you don't worry.

80
00:10:11,725 --> 00:10:16,812
See, there's your anxiety, worry at loss, worry at breakage, breaking down.

81
00:10:19,416 --> 00:10:26,586
So you can see that the more we have, the more we're in for some level of dissatisfaction, some level of suffering.

82
00:10:27,341 --> 00:10:31,285
It's all to do with this attachment, this indulgence.

83
00:10:32,086 --> 00:10:34,309
And the final one is boredom, of course.

84
00:10:34,690 --> 00:10:42,879
Boredom is when we are not getting the same excitement that we used to get from what we're indulging in.

85
00:10:44,140 --> 00:10:46,663
And that boredom is not a nice place to be.

86
00:10:46,683 --> 00:10:48,686
I mean, it's a sort of averse place.

87
00:10:49,125 --> 00:10:51,208
And there's a search for something new.

88
00:10:51,688 --> 00:10:53,431
Variety is the spice of life.

89
00:10:54,292 --> 00:10:56,134
And that's what we do.

90
00:10:56,366 --> 00:11:01,815
one pleasure after another just to keep ourselves occupied, keep ourselves happy.

91
00:11:02,196 --> 00:11:04,158
But this happiness isn't true happiness.

92
00:11:04,578 --> 00:11:15,434
As we see it, it's an excitement based on over, over wanting something more than we actually get from any object.

93
00:11:16,296 --> 00:11:25,529
And that's when we have to remind ourselves that we don't actually want the object so much as the mental state that it produces.

94
00:11:27,873 --> 00:11:39,623
So the three things that we then have to do in order to undermine all this is to distinguish between enjoying something and indulging it.

95
00:11:40,083 --> 00:11:46,349
It's not as though the Buddha is saying we shouldn't enjoy life, we shouldn't enjoy art, nature, friendship and all that sort of stuff.

96
00:11:47,110 --> 00:11:49,312
That's perfectly viable.

97
00:11:49,371 --> 00:11:56,697
He himself enjoyed, for instance, going to shrines, just the normal things of life.

98
00:11:57,673 --> 00:12:02,700
But that distinction is very difficult because indulgence is so close to enjoyment.

99
00:12:02,759 --> 00:12:09,047
I mean, aversion sort of pushes you apart from the object, but indulgence sticks you to it.

100
00:12:10,649 --> 00:12:14,452
The second thing is to begin to distinguish the body from the mind.

101
00:12:14,653 --> 00:12:27,207
And that's all to do with beginning to deconstruct our sense of self, our sense of an identity, our sense of being whole, entire, like an integer, one number.

102
00:12:28,116 --> 00:12:57,211
and uh and the final one which is which is just as important is to distinguish between a desire and an action so we've been we've looked at that a little bit so um that uh just to go back on those um to distinguish between desire and indulgence as i say is difficult so the way you overcome the indulgence is by putting a clear

103
00:12:57,412 --> 00:13:21,057
intention in your mind so this food as the buddha says with this example of the um this uh this uh mother and father who ate their son you know there has to be a real purpose for it uh that food is something to nourish the body for the purpose of becoming liberated it has that spiritual purpose to it

104
00:13:21,525 --> 00:13:27,631
If it has any other purpose, then you have to question it as to whether it's wholesome, whether it's actually leading you on the path.

105
00:13:28,373 --> 00:13:41,767
So every time we're with a cup of tea, with that mythical biscuit, with a meal, we have to sit there for a moment and just remind ourselves, okay, this is to nourish the body, full stop, that's all.

106
00:13:42,227 --> 00:13:45,672
The fact that I enjoy it has to be received as a gift.

107
00:13:46,451 --> 00:13:49,696
You don't have to enjoy food that's nourishing.

108
00:13:49,735 --> 00:13:50,756
It can be quite...

109
00:13:51,344 --> 00:13:51,945
Tasteless.

110
00:13:53,447 --> 00:13:59,195
Porridge without sugar and all that sort of stuff.

111
00:14:00,157 --> 00:14:01,138
So that's the first thing.

112
00:14:01,177 --> 00:14:14,216
And then as you go through the meal, to begin to realize that the excitement that you had at the beginning of the meal is beginning to fade away and there's just this tasting of the food.

113
00:14:15,018 --> 00:14:21,047
So there you're beginning to distinguish the overlay of excitement that we have

114
00:14:21,398 --> 00:14:30,629
when we have a good meal in front of us, and then very slowly over, say, even as little as 10 bites or something, it becomes ordinary.

115
00:14:31,330 --> 00:14:37,476
And then that's the chance to really investigate just enjoying, just enjoying.

116
00:14:38,097 --> 00:14:46,207
And to make that clear to ourselves, we separate the body from the mind, the heart-mind, from feeling, from thinking.

117
00:14:47,841 --> 00:14:55,070
And you do that by driving your attention, first of all, into the body, into the process of tasting and smelling.

118
00:14:55,890 --> 00:15:06,163
And by isolating that physical taste process, you're beginning to realize that this is just the body.

119
00:15:06,943 --> 00:15:12,150
It's the mind that is translating it into something beautiful.

120
00:15:12,910 --> 00:15:16,836
And when you, as it were, swallow, intending to swallow,

121
00:15:17,068 --> 00:15:18,750
And it's dropped, right?

122
00:15:19,812 --> 00:15:22,775
And you stop for a moment and you get the afterglow.

123
00:15:23,115 --> 00:15:25,118
So that afterglow is the mind.

124
00:15:25,499 --> 00:15:39,254
The mind, the heart, the feeling of wellbeing, the feeling of joy is our habituated reaction to the food we're eating.

125
00:15:39,495 --> 00:15:40,395
That's a habit we have.

126
00:15:41,236 --> 00:15:45,961
The habit is to become happy and to indulge, et cetera, the food we're eating.

127
00:15:46,634 --> 00:15:49,698
So it's recognizing that these are two different processes.

128
00:15:52,203 --> 00:16:00,378
And then, as I say, as the meal goes on and the excitement dies out, then one can get close to this business of just enjoyment.

129
00:16:01,259 --> 00:16:08,732
And you might find that when you're just enjoying something, there's a sense of loss because before you really enjoyed it.

130
00:16:09,073 --> 00:16:10,937
See, that's the overlay of excitement.

131
00:16:11,625 --> 00:16:38,847
and then you have to remind yourself well fine i can indulge but then i've got consequence so it's you know it's this constant reminder and eventually of course we find that indulgence is it's it's just too much it's too much sugar you know and you just want to taste things as they are uh without overlaying excitement onto it uh years ago when i was um

132
00:16:39,351 --> 00:16:55,014
teaching at the Birmingham Buddhist Vihara, a young man came, and when he came again the next week, he said that he'd been meditating and he could no longer listen to heavy rock.

133
00:16:55,413 --> 00:17:01,241
So there you can see how refined this young fellow was becoming.

134
00:17:03,504 --> 00:17:07,029
And then the final thing, of course, is action.

135
00:17:07,499 --> 00:17:10,364
the distinction between a desire and an action.

136
00:17:11,226 --> 00:17:31,801
And so when you have your cup of tea, and I would suggest you try and do it at least once a day with a cup of tea and a biscuit or a sandwich, it doesn't matter what, you know, just sit with it, get the feel, get the hunger, feel the hunger, know that some of it is natural appetite, and some of it is

137
00:17:32,035 --> 00:17:42,846
this excitement that we get from indulging, and just stay there with it for a while, and then feel, just feel the force of that desire of wanting to eat.

138
00:17:43,247 --> 00:17:46,730
The more hungry you are, of course, the greater that desire will be.

139
00:17:46,770 --> 00:17:50,515
And then at some point, a decision is made.

140
00:17:50,795 --> 00:17:56,761
A decision is made, something, yes, you know, like you're giving permission for the desire to manifest.

141
00:17:57,301 --> 00:17:59,644
And that manifests through an act of will.

142
00:18:00,105 --> 00:18:01,586
That's your power.

143
00:18:01,836 --> 00:18:06,963
The power is to bring something from potential into actual.

144
00:18:07,444 --> 00:18:09,769
Now, the will itself is completely neutral.

145
00:18:09,828 --> 00:18:10,690
It's just a power.

146
00:18:11,391 --> 00:18:13,594
It's the intention which matters.

147
00:18:14,075 --> 00:18:17,759
It's the intention which is conditioning us.

148
00:18:17,779 --> 00:18:27,954
And it's good to make that distinction and to realize that actually you really can sit with a desire which you don't want until it fades away.

149
00:18:28,615 --> 00:18:31,319
Now, when we sit with a desire,

150
00:18:31,569 --> 00:18:39,277
which we don't want, no matter how strong it is, and wait for it to fade away completely, you get your little gift.

151
00:18:39,636 --> 00:18:44,601
The gift is one of feeling released from it, as if you've been imprisoned or shackled.

152
00:18:45,342 --> 00:18:47,703
And with that, there comes a sense of joy.

153
00:18:48,464 --> 00:18:53,930
But more than that, we're undermining that very habit that we don't want.

154
00:18:54,490 --> 00:19:00,075
And if we keep that going, eventually there comes a point where the habit just doesn't have the force over us.

155
00:19:00,426 --> 00:19:04,554
doesn't have that force and we can just see it come and let it pass.

156
00:19:05,454 --> 00:19:08,941
And that just comes by constant practice.

157
00:19:10,143 --> 00:19:17,253
If we fail, if we find ourselves chucking 10 biscuits down our throats, then it's no point in getting guilty

158
00:19:17,436 --> 00:19:37,023
or feeling horrible about that, you just notice that, well, just for that moment there, you gave in, but then you have to make a firm resolution, a resolute resolution that you'll be very quick to see when that desire arises and just to stay with it, suffer it.

159
00:19:37,284 --> 00:19:39,847
So you've got to suffer.

160
00:19:39,867 --> 00:19:44,453
You've got to stay with the feeling of it until it completely passes away.

161
00:19:46,056 --> 00:19:47,258
And the opposite, of course,

162
00:19:47,592 --> 00:19:50,816
If a desire comes up, which you see is wholesome, then of course you empower it.

163
00:19:51,998 --> 00:19:55,742
Now, just in that very simple way, we can actually change ourselves.

164
00:19:56,503 --> 00:19:58,807
We are nothing but a compendium of habits.

165
00:19:58,826 --> 00:20:00,368
We're just a collection of habits.

166
00:20:00,910 --> 00:20:07,699
And it's a decision to keep some of them, develop some of them, and get rid of the ones we don't want.

167
00:20:08,380 --> 00:20:10,041
And that's just that process.

168
00:20:10,643 --> 00:20:11,724
I'm not saying it's easy.

169
00:20:12,586 --> 00:20:15,809
The stronger the habit, the more

170
00:20:15,976 --> 00:20:21,723
The more established the habit, the more difficult it is to get the better of it.

171
00:20:22,685 --> 00:20:40,431
And eventually, of course, once we're fully awakened, once we're fully liberated from suffering, the traces of that habit might still appear in the heart, the heart-mind, but they just don't have any power over us at all.

172
00:20:44,713 --> 00:20:49,499
So I've tried to put this in a little essay, which I'll post.

173
00:20:49,980 --> 00:20:53,564
I'll post it up onto the website there.

174
00:20:53,584 --> 00:21:02,213
On the front page, again, you'll see next to videos because I've, excuse me, I've gone and posted all the videos up on the website.

175
00:21:02,294 --> 00:21:04,436
Again, you'll see that on the front page.

176
00:21:05,377 --> 00:21:08,721
But somebody told me that you can't download them from there.

177
00:21:08,821 --> 00:21:13,066
It just goes back into YouTube and you have to pay a fee for it.

178
00:21:13,666 --> 00:21:14,468
So...

179
00:21:15,071 --> 00:21:18,756
I'm thinking about how to overcome that.

180
00:21:20,196 --> 00:21:28,925
I've just put one on Dropbox because somebody in New Zealand wanted it and just see if she comes back and says that she was able to download it.

181
00:21:32,028 --> 00:21:32,529
Very good.

182
00:21:33,451 --> 00:21:44,741
So, yes, and the final thing to say is that when we practice this on something so

183
00:21:45,126 --> 00:21:49,272
so obvious as eating, which we have to do every day.

184
00:21:49,292 --> 00:21:50,434
It's not as though you can give up eating.

185
00:21:51,876 --> 00:21:55,382
So it's a constant little practice for us, a constant reminder.

186
00:21:56,663 --> 00:22:14,609
When we do that, we begin to realize that actually this cuts across everything in our lives, you know, in terms of our enjoyment of art, TV, you know, film and all that sort of stuff, our enjoyment of nature, the hobbies we have,

187
00:22:15,855 --> 00:22:21,845
Anything you enjoy, anything you enjoy will have that overlay of wanting something more from it.

188
00:22:22,786 --> 00:22:32,540
And of course, relationship, relationship with its obsessive relationship, the obsessive part.

189
00:22:32,921 --> 00:22:45,019
And that's often manifests in the way that we try to manipulate the other, demand of the other, try to control the other, disappointed in the other, frustrated by the other.

190
00:22:45,251 --> 00:22:46,712
and so on and so forth.

191
00:22:46,732 --> 00:23:01,666
So this practice on just eating, just having a cup of tea with a biscuit will eventually bring that sort of insight into our lives and begin to change it.

192
00:23:02,407 --> 00:23:06,432
And going back to what we said about the Eightfold Path, this is the feedback.

193
